    <p>
      The idea of a climbing challenge in the mountains, specifically Mont Blanc in the summer of 2008, was born early that
      year.
      The story goes like this: Roman, my friend and colleague, tells me he's going to climb Mont Blanc and invites me to
      come along. At first, I say no because the preparation time short for this adventure mountain seems too short.
      However, due to various events, the project is cancelled in the summer of 2008.
      Roman again approaches me about the challenge in September of that year but now it is scheduled for summer 2009. I
      think it would give me enough time and I accept because I realize it's Mont Blanc in 2009 or ... never ...
    </p>
    <p>
      The project is on its way for the two of us who appreciate the mountains and enjoy physical exertion.
      Joining us would be Christophe Romain, a childhood friend of Roman, who is the originator of the climbing project,
      Antoine, my son, and a guide.
    </p>
    <h2>Preparation:</h2>
    <p>
      Such a project requires a guide for safety reasons, a lot of equipment as well as preparation, physically and mentally.
      The climbing team is a little crazy but we have our feet on the ground and we do not want to die right now ...
      The ascent of Mont Blanc differs somewhat from a beach and such an adventure requires special
      equipment including crampons, ice axes and thermal underwear to SURVIVE in a hostile environment.
      The normal/usual weather is -10 ° C, sunny with sudden changes that can bring down the temperature to -40 °C.
      Needless to say, wearing a swimsuit is inappropriate so we buy all the equipment in a sporting goods store.
      Once equipped, we can now move on to more serious things: preparing for the weekend. A program is put together with,
      depending on our schedule, a more or less intense workout.
    </p>
    <p>
      So we range over the following mountains: Vallée Blanche (ski course and ice), Gran Paradiso, the Puy de Sancy,
      the Breithorm, Castor and Pollux before embarking on the slopes of Mont Blanc (Or four peaks over 4,000 m). Antoine,
      the youngest, trains less due to his distance from the mountains. (But after the climb everyone realizes that he was
      prepared enough for the climb... The advantage of youth... )
    </p>
    <h2>D-Day:</h2>
    <p>
      On Saturday, July 11, 2009 the four of us wait at the refuge de Tête Rousse for our two guides, Olivier
      and Olivier, who arrive late the next day. On Sunday morning they catch the first train to Mont Blanc from Saint
      Gervais and arrive at the terminus called the "Eagle's Nest at 2362 m altitude". Now there are approximately two
      hours of hiking up 800m altitude to reach us at the Tête Rousse shelter located at 3,167 m. Our guides arrive at
      10am which is a late start to climb such a summit.
      Due the wind and clouds we are forced to abandon the climb to the summit and back in one day as originally planned.
      Our guides decide to climb to shelter called Gouter at 3817 m altitude despite that there is no room available.
      They hope that some climbers will decide to go down due to the weather.
      We arrive at Goûter at 13:00, the weather is bad, we eat and then we play cards in the afternoon
      hoping for better weather for tomorrow. It is 8-10 ° in the shelter ... we keep our jackets and caps on while we
      strategize when we should start our climb to Mount Blanc.
      At 21:30 no bed is available so we sleep a little tightly in the dormitory of the guides.
    </p>
    <p>
      Finally, they tell us to get some sleep/rest and they will get up at 3 am to CHECK the weather. If it's good
      they will wake us, otherwise they will get us up at 6am to leave by 7am. Finally the night is
      going "normally" as you would expect in a shelter, that MEANS not very good: light sleep and when you can sleep.
      At 2:00 am, the place is rocking but we remain asleep. Our guides wake up at 6am and
      inform us that all the parties that left at 3 have returned without reaching the top due to clouds and winds ...
      We have breakfast and then in two groups holding on to a rope we head into the fog.
      Bad weather continues for two hours, with the wind blowing at 70km an hour. The arrival at the refuge Vallot
      (unsupervised) at an altitude of 4362 m is a bit supernatural. In this fog, and with the shelter made of aluminum
      plates we seem to be entering a spacecraft. After a 15 minute minute break, we emerge from the spacecraft and
      behold... there is a miracle! The fog has lifted, revealing some blue sky.
    </p>
    <p>
      And we begin the final part of the climb. At this altitude, the air is less dense, every
      step requires a significant effort, and as we go slowly, I feel no progress. I
      look at the altimeter from time to time,"Come on, only 100m". I don't want to keep looking at the
      altimeter too often for fear of discouragement. I think we've reached the top, and then no, it's a long ridge to climb ...
      I stop, stopping everyone else, to breath some air ... the guides tell me to continue. We press on our
      slow ascent until finally, 10 minutes later we arrived at the summit of Mont Blanc.
    </p>
    <p>
      The summit is not a big bump as I thought, but a fine edge on which we must stand with the help of
      our picks. We do not have time to get out our cameras before the clouds arrive. Only one of two guides
      has taker a picture of the "cloudless" summit. He is a better photographer and faster ...
      Happiness is at the top, the reward for a lot of determination and long hours of preparation. Finally, one of those
      moments that forge the friendship among us and which remains a special moment between a
      father and his son.
      We take the photograph with the Nexter banner.
    </p>
    <p>
      So, this photo was not taken in a Hammam....
      Then, we start the descent. This goes faster, but this is tiring nonetheless. Our two roped groups
      overtake each other from time to time.
      During the passages where it's possible, this is a little game of relax and rivalry. We do not come
      across another roped group. We only come across one person when we arrive AT Gouter. We have
      been one of the rare roped groups to reach the Mont Blanc this day, maybe the only one ... Our guides
      have made the right choice for the departure time and my fear of having to cross a group roped on
      the edges of Mont Blanc was unjustified . So, this shows that the Mont Blanc is not always frequented, due to the weather.
    </p>
    <p>
      After the successful descent it was time to celebrate with a meal in Goûter at midday. After lunch we continued down to the refuge de Tête Rousse, contending with lots of rocks and then we crossed "the corridor of death" named appropriately due to the random falling rocks. It seemed that every three minutes one of these projectiles hurtled toward us. Labor unions would definitely oppose such dangerous working conditions. If this were our job. But of course this is not the case; we are on holidays and we have every right to take risks.
      With the exception of death row, I never felt like my life was in danger.
      However, when we learn that during the following week, a roped group of three people (including the
      guide) plunged to their death down the passage between the rocks of le Gouter and Tete Rousse.
      (resulting in 3 causalities)
    </p>
    <h2>In conclusion....</h2>
    <p>
      The success of such a climb is the culmination of lengthy preparation, the luck of good weather, and
      the reward of a long and sustained physical effort. Other rewards gained during the climb are images imprinted in one's mind of mountainous landscapes and intense moments shared among kindred spirits who have the same passion. It all adds up to happiness.
    </p>
    <h2>Future plans:</h2>
    <p>
      We may do a new climb in the Alps in the summer of 2010.
      Christophe and Romain are preparing the climb of Mount Rose and the Dome Miage.
      For me, I am waiting for the Dome de Miage with Romain and Christopher. However, my current
      health status may prevent me from making this climb.
      This is also this thing the ascent of a summit: the joy of being physically able to climb a mountain
      and the impermanence of this moment.
    </p>
